{{Other people|Billy Murray}} {{Use mdy dates|date=April 2013}} {{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians --> | name = Billy Murray | image = BillyMurrayEdisonMay1911 crop.jpg | image_size = | caption = Murray in May 1911 | background = solo_singer | birth_name = William Thomas Murray | birth_date = {{birth date|1877|5|25}} | birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], United States | origin = New York City | death_date = {{Death date and age|1954|8|17|1877|5|25}} | death_place = [[Jones Beach State Park|Jones Beach]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States | genre = [[Popular music|Pop]] | occupation = Musician | instrument = Singer | years_active = 1899–1943 | label = [[Okeh Records|OkeH]] | associated_acts = }}
'''William Thomas "Billy" Murray''' (May 25, 1877 – August 17, 1954) was one of the most popular singers in the United States in the early 20th century.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ruhlmann|first=William|title=Billy Murray|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/billy-murray-p375938|work=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=October 14, 2011}}</ref> While he received star billing in [[vaudeville]], he was best known for his prolific work in the recording studio, making records for almost every [[record label]] of the era.
==Life and career== Billy Murray was born in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] to Patrick and Julia (Kelleher) Murray, immigrants from [[County Kerry]], Ireland.<ref>US Census, 1880, 24th Ward, District 21, Philadelphia, PA</ref><ref name=biography>{{cite web|title=Billy Murray: A Biography|url=http://www.denvernightingale.com/biography.html|work=The Official Website of Billy Murray (1877-1954)|publisher=Phonostalgia |accessdate=October 14, 2011}}</ref> His parents moved to [[Denver, Colorado]] in 1882, where he grew up. He became fascinated with the theater and joined a traveling vaudeville troupe in 1893. He also performed in [[minstrel show]]s early in his career. In 1897 Murray made his first recordings for Peter Bacigalupi, the owner of a phonograph company in San Francisco. As of 2010 none of Murray's cylinder records with Bacigalupi are known to have survived.<ref name="biography" /> In 1903, he started recording regularly in New York City and [[New Jersey]] area, where major record companies in the U.S. as well as the [[Tin Pan Alley]] music industry were concentrated.
In 1906, he recorded the first of his popular duets with [[Ada Jones]]. He also performed with [[Aileen Stanley]], the [[Haydn Quartet (vocal ensemble)|Haydn Quartet]], the [[American Quartet (ensemble)|American Quartet]] (also known as the Premier Quartet), and [[Elsie Baker]] as well as performed solo work.
Nicknamed "The Denver Nightingale", Murray had a strong [[tenor]] voice with excellent enunciation and a conversational delivery compared with [[bel canto]] singers of the era. On comic songs, he often deliberately sang slightly flat, which he felt helped the comic effect. Although he often performed romantic numbers and ballads which sold well, his comedy and [[novelty song]] recordings continue to be popular with later generations of record collectors. [[File:BillyMurrayEmerson1919.JPG|thumb|left|300px|Billy Murray newspaper ad from 1919]] Murray was a devoted baseball fan, and he is said to have played with the [[New York Yankees|New York Highlanders (Yankees)]] in exhibition games. He also supposedly sometimes called in sick to recording sessions in order to go to the ballpark. Murray recorded "Tessie, You Are the Only, Only, Only", which became the unofficial theme of the [[1903 World Series]], when the words were changed from "Tessie, you know I love you madly" to "[[Honus Wagner|Honus]], why do you hit so badly?"
Murray's popularity faded as public taste changed and recording technology advanced; the rise of the electric [[microphone]] in the mid-1920s coincided with the era of the [[crooner]]s. His "hammering" style, as he called it, essentially yelling the song into an acoustic recording horn, did not work in the electrical era, and he had to learn to soften his voice. {{listen | filename = Billy Murray - K-K-K-Katy.ogg | title = K-K-K-Katy | description = performed by Billy Murray (Recorded in 1918) | format = [[Ogg]] | filename2 = Billy Murray - You're a Grand Old Flag.ogg | title2 = You're a Grand Old Flag | description2 = Performed by Billy Murray (Recorded in 1906) | format2 = [[Ogg]] | filename3 = Are You from Dixie ('Cause I'm from Dixie Too).ogg | title3 = Are You from Dixie ('Cause I'm from Dixie Too) | description3 = performed by Billy Murray (Recorded in 1916) | format3 = [[ogg]] | pos = right }} Though his singing style was less in demand, he continued to find recording work. By the late 1920s and early 1930s, the music from his early days was considered nostalgic, and Murray was in demand again. He did voices for [[animated cartoon]]s, especially the popular "follow the bouncing ball" sing-along cartoons and the [[Fleischer Studios]] character [[Bimbo (Fleischer)|Bimbo]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://lantz.goldenagecartoons.com/1930.html |title = The Walter Lantz Cartune Encyclopedia: 1930 |accessdate = 2011-04-24 |publisher = The Walter Lantz Cartune Encyclopedia |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110514224259/http://lantz.goldenagecartoons.com/1930.html |archivedate = May 14, 2011 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> He also did radio work.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barna|first=Ryan|title=BILLY MURRAY'S RADIO PROGRAMS: Walter Scanlon and Marcella Shields|url=http://www.denvernightingale.com/radio.html|work=The Official Website of Billy Murray (1877-1954)|publisher=Phonostalgia|accessdate=October 14, 2011}}</ref> In 1929, Murray and [[Walter Scanlon]] provided the voices for the Fleischer short animation film ''[[Finding His Voice]]'', produced by [[Western Electric]].
Murray made his last recordings for Beacon Records on February 11, 1943 with Jewish dialect comedian [[Monroe Silver]]. He retired the next year to [[Freeport, New York|Freeport]], [[Long Island]], New York because of heart problems. He died at nearby [[Jones Beach State Park|Jones Beach]] of a heart attack in 1954 at the age of 77. Murray had married three times, the first two ending in divorce. He was survived by his third wife, Madeleine, and is buried in the [[Cemetery of the Holy Rood]] in [[Westbury, New York]].<ref name=biography />
==In popular culture== Decades later, "You're a Grand Old Rag", and "Shine On, Harvest Moon", two of his songs would be heard in [[BioShock Infinite]]. the former being heard faintly in one of the reveal trailers, and the latter being heard in The Fellow Traveller Pub.{{cn|date=March 2018}}
